From b94f3ddbe60465651b51b2d166192b2f50502283 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: operations-jacrentals <operations@jacrentals.com>
Date: Sat, 18 Jul 2026 21:37:15 -0500
Subject: [PATCH] Gate and confirm the destructive card/bank and membership
 money actions
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Four money controls could be fired by a single click, three of them by any
logged-in role. Adding a card was already Office/Admin-only via canMoney();
changing or deleting one was not — the wrong way round, especially since
removeCard also fires a live stripeRemoveCard detach and is therefore not
locally reversible. Only 124 cards exist across 2,265 customers.

A1 — js-card-default, js-card-remove, js-bank-default, js-bank-remove now
     carry the same canMoney() gate and toast as their js-add-card /
     js-add-ach siblings. The two removes additionally arm-to-confirm.
A3 — js-mem-cancel arms to confirm before ending a paying membership and
     raising a cancellation invoice for the remainder of the term.
A2 — js-mem-paycxl arms to confirm before charging the card in full, and the
     armed label states the amount.

All four reuse the existing js-blacklist arm-to-confirm shape (set
dataset.armed, relabel, act on the second click) — no new CSS, no new
component.

DELIBERATE DEVIATION: the audit proposed routing js-mem-paycxl through
openPayInvoice to get a review overlay. That would be wrong.
membershipReactivate does not merely charge the cancellation invoice — it
also calls backendCall('membershipReactivate', ...) and reopens the
membership (accountType / paidUntil / prepaid / graceUntil). openPayInvoice
only charges an invoice, so re-pointing the button would take the customer's
money and leave their membership lapsed. Arm-to-confirm gets the same
protection without touching the reactivation path.

CONTEXT for review: js-blacklist is deliberately ungated — "spec
customers-crm D3: ANY role can blacklist; the audit trail is the control".
removeCard/removeBank do call logAction, so an audit-trail-only argument
could be made for them too. The asymmetry with the already-gated add path,
plus the irreversible Stripe detach, is why this gates them instead. Say the
word if you'd rather they follow D3.

Visible change: below-Office roles now get a toast instead of the action;
Office/Admin get one extra click on the four destructive controls.

Gates: smoke, logic-test, lease-test, lease-deploy-test, promote-test,
deck-test, cachebust-test, gen-rule-usage --check, check-window-catalog,
check-cachebust, check-design-md, gen-code-map --check — all green.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
